{"parse":{"title":"Chromatic fourth","pageid":5589334,"revid":855668424,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">For Chromatic tetrachord, see <a href=\"/wiki/Chromatic_genus\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Chromatic genus\">Chromatic genus</a>.</div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Chopin-_Prelude_in_C_Minor_mm.5-6_chromatic_run.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Chopin-_Prelude_in_C_Minor_mm.5-6_chromatic_run.png/220px-Chopin-_Prelude_in_C_Minor_mm.5-6_chromatic_run.png\" width=\"220\" height=\"113\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Chopin-_Prelude_in_C_Minor_mm.5-6_chromatic_run.png/330px-Chopin-_Prelude_in_C_Minor_mm.5-6_chromatic_run.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Chopin-_Prelude_in_C_Minor_mm.5-6_chromatic_run.png/440px-Chopin-_Prelude_in_C_Minor_mm.5-6_chromatic_run.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"2065\" data-file-height=\"1059\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Chopin-_Prelude_in_C_Minor_mm.5-6_chromatic_run.png\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Chromatic run from Chopin's Prelude in C Minor, mm.5-6.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> <span class=\"unicode haudio\"><span class=\"fn\"><span style=\"white-space:nowrap\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Chopin-_Prelude_in_C_Minor_mm.5-6_chromatic_run.mid\" title=\"About this sound\"><img alt=\"About this sound\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png\" width=\"11\" height=\"11\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/17px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/22px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"20\" data-file-height=\"20\" /></a>&#160;</span><a href=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/bf/Chopin-_Prelude_in_C_Minor_mm.5-6_chromatic_run.mid\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Chopin- Prelude in C Minor mm.5-6 chromatic run.mid\">Play</a></span>&#160;<small class=\"metadata audiolinkinfo\" style=\"cursor:help;\">(<a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Media_help\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wikipedia:Media help\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">help</span></a>\u00b7<a href=\"/wiki/File:Chopin-_Prelude_in_C_Minor_mm.5-6_chromatic_run.mid\" title=\"File:Chopin- Prelude in C Minor mm.5-6 chromatic run.mid\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">info</span></a>)</small></span></div></div></div>\n<p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Music\" title=\"Music\">music</a>, a <b>chromatic fourth</b>, or <i><b>passus duriusculus</b></i>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Monelle_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Monelle-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Melody\" title=\"Melody\">melody</a> or melodic fragment spanning a <a href=\"/wiki/Perfect_fourth\" title=\"Perfect fourth\">perfect fourth</a> with all or almost all <a href=\"/wiki/Chromatic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Chromatic\">chromatic</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Interval_(music)\" title=\"Interval (music)\">intervals</a> filled in (<a href=\"/wiki/Chromatic_line\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Chromatic line\">chromatic line</a>). The quintessential example is in <a href=\"/wiki/D_minor\" title=\"D minor\">D minor</a> with the tonic and dominant notes as boundaries, <span class=\"unicode haudio\"><span class=\"fn\"><span style=\"white-space:nowrap\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Chrom4th_Example.mid\" title=\"About this sound\"><img alt=\"About this sound\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png\" width=\"11\" height=\"11\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/17px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/22px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"20\" data-file-height=\"20\" /></a>&#160;</span><a href=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8f/Chrom4th_Example.mid\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Chrom4th Example.mid\">Play</a></span>&#160;<small class=\"metadata audiolinkinfo\" style=\"cursor:help;\">(<a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Media_help\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wikipedia:Media help\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">help</span></a>\u00b7<a href=\"/wiki/File:Chrom4th_Example.mid\" title=\"File:Chrom4th Example.mid\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">info</span></a>)</small></span>:\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/File:Chrom4th_Example.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Chrom4th Example.png\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/a/a5/Chrom4th_Example.png\" width=\"267\" height=\"57\" data-file-width=\"267\" data-file-height=\"57\" /></a>\n</p><p>The chromatic fourth was first used in the <a href=\"/wiki/Madrigal_(music)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Madrigal (music)\">madrigals</a> of the 16th Century.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (June 2011)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> The Latin term itself\u2014\"harsh\" or \"difficult\" (<i>duriusculus</i>) \"step\" or \"passage\" (<i>passus</i>)\u2014originates in <a href=\"/wiki/Christoph_Bernhard\" title=\"Christoph Bernhard\">Christoph Bernhard</a>'s 17th century <i>Tractatus compositionis augmentatus</i> (1648\u201349), where it appears to refer to repeated melodic motion by semitone creating consecutive semitones.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Monelle_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Monelle-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The term may also relate to the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Pianto\" title=\"Pianto\">pianto</a></i> associated with weeping.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Monelle_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Monelle-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> In the Baroque, <a href=\"/wiki/Johann_Sebastian_Bach\" title=\"Johann Sebastian Bach\">Johann Sebastian Bach</a> used it in his choral as well as his instrumental music, in the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Well-Tempered_Clavier\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Well-Tempered Clavier\">Well-Tempered Clavier</a></i>, for example (the chromatic fourth is indicated by a red bracket), <span class=\"unicode haudio\"><span class=\"fn\"><span style=\"white-space:nowrap\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Bach_Example_wHiLite.mid\" title=\"About this sound\"><img alt=\"About this sound\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png\" width=\"11\" height=\"11\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/17px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/22px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"20\" data-file-height=\"20\" /></a>&#160;</span><a href=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/ae/Bach_Example_wHiLite.mid\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Bach Example wHiLite.mid\">Play</a></span>&#160;<small class=\"metadata audiolinkinfo\" style=\"cursor:help;\">(<a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Media_help\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wikipedia:Media help\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">help</span></a>\u00b7<a href=\"/wiki/File:Bach_Example_wHiLite.mid\" title=\"File:Bach Example wHiLite.mid\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">info</span></a>)</small></span>:\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/File:Bach_Example_wHiLite.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Bach Example wHiLite.png\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/d/d1/Bach_Example_wHiLite.png/400px-Bach_Example_wHiLite.png\" width=\"400\" height=\"71\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/d/d1/Bach_Example_wHiLite.png 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"401\" data-file-height=\"71\" /></a>\n</p><p>In operas of the Baroque and Classical, the chromatic fourth was often used in the bass and for woeful arias, often being called a \"<a href=\"/wiki/Lament_bass\" title=\"Lament bass\">lament bass</a>\". In the penultimate pages of the first movement of <a href=\"/wiki/Beethoven\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Beethoven\">Beethoven</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/Symphony_No._9_(Beethoven)\" title=\"Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)\">Ninth Symphony</a>, the  chromatic fourth appears in the cellos and basses.\n</p>\n<div class=\"center\"><div class=\"thumb tnone\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:402px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Vivaldi_lament_bass_from_RV_631,_Aria_No._2.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Vivaldi_lament_bass_from_RV_631%2C_Aria_No._2.png/400px-Vivaldi_lament_bass_from_RV_631%2C_Aria_No._2.png\" width=\"400\" height=\"132\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Vivaldi_lament_bass_from_RV_631%2C_Aria_No._2.png/600px-Vivaldi_lament_bass_from_RV_631%2C_Aria_No._2.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Vivaldi_lament_bass_from_RV_631%2C_Aria_No._2.png/800px-Vivaldi_lament_bass_from_RV_631%2C_Aria_No._2.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1698\" data-file-height=\"561\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Vivaldi_lament_bass_from_RV_631,_Aria_No._2.png\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Lament bass from <a href=\"/wiki/Antonio_Vivaldi\" title=\"Antonio Vivaldi\">Vivaldi</a>'s motet <i>\"O qui coeli terraeque serenitas\"</i> <a href=\"/wiki/Ryom-Verzeichnis\" title=\"Ryom-Verzeichnis\">RV</a> 631, Aria No. 2<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> <span class=\"unicode haudio\"><span class=\"fn\"><span style=\"white-space:nowrap\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Vivaldi_lament_bass_from_RV_631,_Aria_No._2.mid\" title=\"About this sound\"><img alt=\"About this sound\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png\" width=\"11\" height=\"11\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/17px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/22px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"20\" data-file-height=\"20\" /></a>&#160;</span><a href=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/16/Vivaldi_lament_bass_from_RV_631%2C_Aria_No._2.mid\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Vivaldi lament bass from RV 631, Aria No. 2.mid\">Play</a></span>&#160;<small class=\"metadata audiolinkinfo\" style=\"cursor:help;\">(<a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Media_help\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wikipedia:Media help\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">help</span></a>\u00b7<a href=\"/wiki/File:Vivaldi_lament_bass_from_RV_631,_Aria_No._2.mid\" title=\"File:Vivaldi lament bass from RV 631, Aria No. 2.mid\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">info</span></a>)</small></span>.</div></div></div></div>\n<p>This does not mean that the chromatic fourth was always used in a sorrowful or foreboding way, or that the boundaries should always be the tonic and dominant notes. One counterexample comes from the Minuet of <a href=\"/wiki/Wolfgang_Amadeus_Mozart\" title=\"Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart\">Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/String_Quartet_No._14_(Mozart)\" title=\"String Quartet No. 14 (Mozart)\">String Quartet in G major</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/K%C3%B6chel_number\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"K\u00f6chel number\">K.</a> 387 (the chromatic fourths are conveniently bracketed by the slurs and set apart with note-to-note dynamics changes), <span class=\"unicode haudio\"><span class=\"fn\"><span style=\"white-space:nowrap\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:K387m2_IVln.mid\" title=\"About this sound\"><img alt=\"About this sound\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png\" width=\"11\" height=\"11\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/17px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/22px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"20\" data-file-height=\"20\" /></a>&#160;</span><a href=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/65/K387m2_IVln.mid\" class=\"internal\" title=\"K387m2 IVln.mid\">Play</a></span>&#160;<small class=\"metadata audiolinkinfo\" style=\"cursor:help;\">(<a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Media_help\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wikipedia:Media help\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">help</span></a>\u00b7<a href=\"/wiki/File:K387m2_IVln.mid\" title=\"File:K387m2 IVln.mid\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">info</span></a>)</small></span>:\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/File:K387m2_IVln.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"K387m2 IVln.png\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f7/K387m2_IVln.png/400px-K387m2_IVln.png\" width=\"400\" height=\"63\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f7/K387m2_IVln.png 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"480\" data-file-height=\"76\" /></a>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Musical_works_using_the_chromatic_fourth_or_passus_duriusculus\">Musical works using the chromatic fourth or <i>passus duriusculus</i></span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Chromatic_fourth&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Musical works using the chromatic fourth or passus duriusculus\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:352px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Bwv614-preview.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Bwv614-preview.jpg/350px-Bwv614-preview.jpg\" width=\"350\" height=\"68\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Bwv614-preview.jpg/525px-Bwv614-preview.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Bwv614-preview.jpg/700px-Bwv614-preview.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"772\" data-file-height=\"150\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Bwv614-preview.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>In the organ chorale prelude BWV 614, there are chromatic fourths in the three accompanying voices</div></div></div>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Dido%27s_Lament\" title=\"Dido&#39;s Lament\">Henry Purcell, \"Dido's Lament\"</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-Monelle_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Monelle-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Mass_in_B_minor_structure#Crucifixus\" title=\"Mass in B minor structure\">J. S. Bach, Mass in B minor, Crucifixus</a>, also <a href=\"/wiki/BWV_12\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"BWV 12\">BWV 12, \"Weinen, Klagen, Sorgen, Zagen\"</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/BWV_78\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"BWV 78\">J. S. Bach, BWV 78: \"Jesu, der du meine Seele\"</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/BWV_150\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"BWV 150\">J. S. Bach, BWV 150: \"Nach Dir, Herr, verlanget mich\"</a> (in the first choral, and a reverse, <i>whole note upwards</i> melody in the final Chaconne)</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Johann_Sebastian_Bach\" title=\"Johann Sebastian Bach\">J. S. Bach</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/BWV_614\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"BWV 614\">Orgelb\u00fcchlein, BWV 614</a>: \"Das Alte Jahr vergangen ist\" (in the three accompanying voices) <span class=\"unicode haudio\"><span class=\"fn\"><span style=\"white-space:nowrap\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:BWV614-organ.mid\" title=\"About this sound\"><img alt=\"About this sound\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png\" width=\"11\" height=\"11\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/17px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/22px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"20\" data-file-height=\"20\" /></a>&#160;</span><a href=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c0/BWV614-organ.mid\" class=\"internal\" title=\"BWV614-organ.mid\">play</a></span>&#160;<small class=\"metadata audiolinkinfo\" style=\"cursor:help;\">(<a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Media_help\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wikipedia:Media help\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">help</span></a>\u00b7<a href=\"/wiki/File:BWV614-organ.mid\" title=\"File:BWV614-organ.mid\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">info</span></a>)</small></span></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Johann_Sebastian_Bach\" title=\"Johann Sebastian Bach\">J. S. Bach</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Inventions_and_Sinfonias_(Bach)\" title=\"Inventions and Sinfonias (Bach)\">Invention No. 9 in F minor, BWV 795</a> (second subject)</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Johann_Sebastian_Bach\" title=\"Johann Sebastian Bach\">J. S. Bach</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Prelude_and_Fugue_in_C-sharp_minor,_BWV_849\" title=\"Prelude and Fugue in C-sharp minor, BWV 849\">Prelude and Fugue in C-sharp minor, BWV 849</a>, second voice in bar 69, soprano in bar 71</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Wolfgang_Amadeus_Mozart\" title=\"Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart\">W. A. Mozart</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Adagio_and_Allegro_in_F_minor_for_a_mechanical_organ,_K._594\" title=\"Adagio and Allegro in F minor for a mechanical organ, K. 594\">K. 594: \"St\u00fcck f\u00fcr ein Orgelwerk in einer Uhr\"</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Fr%C3%A9d%C3%A9ric_Chopin\" title=\"Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Chopin\">Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Chopin</a>, No. 15 from <a href=\"/wiki/Preludes_(Chopin)\" title=\"Preludes (Chopin)\">24 Preludes</a>, Op. 28</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Hector_Berlioz\" title=\"Hector Berlioz\">Hector Berlioz</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Requiem_(Berlioz)\" title=\"Requiem (Berlioz)\">Requiem, Op. 5</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/C%C3%A9sar_Franck\" title=\"C\u00e9sar Franck\">C\u00e9sar Franck</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Pr%C3%A9lude,_Choral_et_Fugue_(Franck)\" title=\"Pr\u00e9lude, Choral et Fugue (Franck)\">Prelude, Chorale and Fugue<